@NODE "ToolTypes" "RoboDocBuilderPPC ToolTypes:"
@PREV main

   The Icon ToolTypes allow RoboDocBuilderPPC to find information about
   how the program is configured on your Amiga System.
   
   ToolType:         Default:
   ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~   ~~~~~~~~
   @{" TABSIZE         " LINK TabSize} = 3
   @{" TOOLEDITOR      " LINK "ToolTypesEditor.guide/Main"} = ToolTypesEditorPPC
   @{" BUILDCOMMAND    " LINK BuildCommand} = RoboDoc
   @{" TEMPLATEPATH    " LINK TemplatePath} = RoboDoc:RoboDocTemplates
   @{" COMMANDPATH     " LINK CommandPath} = C:
   @{" STRINGIDCHAR    " LINK StringIDChar} = $                      (NOT Currently used)
   @{" DEFAULTEDITOR   " LINK DefaultEditor} = C:Ed
   @{" DEFAULTLANGUAGE " LINK DefaultLanguage} = C                      (NOT Currently used) @{FG SHINE}     
                        Other allowed values:  (ASSY | BASIC | FORTRAN | LATEX 
                                                     | TEX   | POSTSCRIPT) @{FG TEXT}
   @{" DEFAULTOUTPUT   " LINK DefaultOutput} = GUIDE @{FG SHINE}
                        Other allowed values:  (ASCII | HTML | LATEX | RTF) @{FG TEXT}

   The philosophy behind using ToolTypes (for me at least) is to specify
   program configuration inside the Icon & eliminate the necessity for
   spreading files throughout your filing system, such as the C: directory
   for executables, the S: or ENV: directory for preferences files, etc.

   See Also, @{" ToolTypesEditorPPC " LINK "ToolTypesEditor.guide/Main"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE DefaultOutput "DefaultOutput ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes

   The DefaultOutput ToolType allows RoboDocBuilder to check the 
   appropriate MenuItem found in the @{B}Output Type »@{UB}
   Menu Section.  Recognized values are:

     @{" ASCII " LINK "AsciiOutType"}
     @{" Guide " LINK "AGuideOutType"} - AmigaGuide (Default)
     @{" HTML  " LINK "HTMLOutType"}
     @{" LaTeX " LINK "LatexOutType"}
     @{" RTF   " LINK "RTFOutType"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE BuildCommand "BuildCommand ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes

   If the name of RoboDoc should change in the future (or you simply 
   want to rename it something that's more meaningful to you), set
   BuildCommand to the actual name of the RoboDoc program.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DefaultLanguage "DefaultLanguage ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes

   The DefaultLanguage ToolType allows you to specify what the source
   language is that RoboDocBuilderPPC should expect.

   Currently, RoboDocBuilderPPC does NOT use this ToolType for any operations.
   
   The default language is @{B}C@{UB}.  Valid choices are:
   
   Assembly   - Any assembler that uses @{B}*@{UB} or @{B};@{UB} as comment 
                delimiters.
   C          - My personal favorite.
   BASIC      - Any dialect that recognizes REM statements.
   FORTRAN    - Any dialect that uses @{B}C@{UB} as comment delimiters.
   LaTeX      - Text Formatting language.
   TeX        - Text formatting language.
   PostScript - A printer programming language.

@ENDNODE

@NODE StringIDChar "StringIDChar ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes
@NEXT main

   The StringIDChar ToolType specifies a substitution marker that's used
   in Templates, for locating points in your template where substitution
   strings can be placed.

   The default character is @{B}$@{UB}, because it's not used in C or 
   assembly identifier strings.

   Currently, RoboDocBuilderPPC does NOT use this ToolType for any operations.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TemplatePath "Template Path ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes
@NEXT main

   The TemplatePath ToolType tells RoboDocBuilderPPC where to find the
   template files that you wish to use.  Thus, different projects can
   have their own template directories.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DefaultEditor "Default Editor ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes
@NEXT main

   The DefaultEditor ToolType allows you to specify what text editor 
   RoboDocBuilderPPC should call when text has to be edited.

   The default editor is @{B}C:Ed@{UB}

@ENDNODE

@NODE CommandPath "Command Path ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes
@NEXT main

   The CommandPath ToolType tells RoboDocBuilderPPC where to find any
   support programs that come with it.  This eliminates the need to
   clutter up your Sys:C/ directory further.  In other words, you can
   specify (with the install script) where to place RoboDocBuilderPPC
   support programs, such as ToolTypesEditorPPC.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TabSize "TabSize ToolType:"
@PREV ToolTypes
@NEXT main

   This ToolType specifies the size of tab characters that RoboDoc will
   use with its @{B}TABSIZE@{UB} flag.  Printers, AmigaDOS, & Text editors
   all use different sizes for Tab characters.  If you substitute spaces, 
   you eliminate these differences (translation:  @{B}Don't use tabs!@{UB}).

@ENDNODE

